03555nam a22005295i 9780804778947DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047789477 a10.1515/97808047789472doi  a(DE-B1597)564629  a(OCoLC)1198930529  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPR468.P55 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/3579a820.935791 aKaiser, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe World in Play :bPortraits of a Victorian Concept /cMatthew Kaiser. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: A Modern Sensation -- t1. Mapping the World in Play -- t2. Fair Play in an Ugly World: The Politics of Nautical Melodrama -- t3. Toying with the Future in Wuthering Heights -- t4. A Joy on the Precipice of Death: Muir and Stevenson in California -- t5. Wilde's Folly -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNineteenth-century Britain was a world in play. The Victorians invented the weekend and built hundreds of parks and playgrounds. In the wake of Darwin, they re-imagined nature as a contest for survival. The playful child became a symbol of the future. A world in play means two things: a world in flux and a world trapped, like Alice in Wonderland, in a ludic microcosm of itself. The book explores the extent to which play (competition, leisure, mischief, luck, festivity, imagination) pervades nineteenth-century literature and culture and forms the foundations of the modern self. Play made the Victorian world cohere and betrayed the illusoriness of that coherence. This is the paradox of modernity. Kaiser gives an account of how certain Victorian misfits-working-class melodramatists of the 1830s, the reclusive Emily Brontë, free spirits Robert Louis Stevenson and John Muir, mischievous Oscar Wilde-struggled to make sense of this new world. In so doing, they discovered the art of modern life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPlay in literaturexCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aPlay in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804778947zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778947.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles